l policies. McGee argues that the 1982 move away from the DREE model of regional development was a mistake, and suggests that the predilection of governments for reorganising existing instruments of regional development policy and creating new ones has been detrimental to regional economies. Mindful of the new realities of the global economy within which Canada and its regions must compete, and of the promise/threat of rapidly changing technology, McGee identifies the need for a new order of priorities with which governments can meet these challenges and opportunities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticzCanada. 0aRegional planningzCanada. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Public Finance.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356351340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773563513423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773563513/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles